fields.description:
Would be nice to be able to generate a contact details table via a macro to list the team members and their contact details.
{contact-details:group=moo-developers|contact-details=fullname;email}

In conjunction with CONF-3017, you could then do something like:
{contact-details:group=moo-developers|contact-details=fullname;email;phone;location}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-3018].
  {panel}

Currently [~username] renders a link to the user's profile.
What would be nice is to be able to generate, directly, an email link - ala [~username:email] - which will generate a mailto link to that user's email address.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2966].
  {panel}

The progress meter should be incorporated within each page that can currently call it. It should no longer occupy its own page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2959].
  {panel}

This is similar to TST-459 except that I'd like a more "classical bread crumbs" that shows the last pages visited and not the hierarchy.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2956].
  {panel}

It would be nice to have a macro that displays the count of the children of the page. I would like to use this, along with {children:excerpt=true} to display more info about the children of the page. For example, I want to list the children and also show how many children each child page has (i.e. grandchildren). For branchy tree organization, this is useful to help navigate the tree, so you see which branches have lots of children. Workaround is to use depth parameter on children macro, but for branchy hierarchies, this can take up a lot of space.

We need to add some kind of "refactorable" interface to macros, so that they can intelligently rename themselves when they refer to pages.

Affected macros include:

{excerpt-include}
{include}
{children} (when listing another page)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2936].
  {panel}

Currently, the {junitreport} macro only works against individual <testsuite> elements, not grouped <testsuites>

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2906].
  {panel}

When I rename (move) a Confluence page, could we get Confluence to respond with a 301 ("permanent redirect") HTTP response, instead of a "Page Not Found"?  This seems both more consistent with the HTTP designers' intentions, and more convenient for users.
